of Mimesis, Auerbach still stands as a touchstone for contemporary academic debates on the place of historical criticism in the construction of literary history, on the relations between intellectual activity and political action, and on the function of the critic in recording—or effecting—social change. More than an occasion to review past accomplishments or revel in the nostalgias of prewar Marburg or postwar New Haven, the papers offered in this volume seek to reassess Auerbach's work and his example for the modern academic. Their genesis lay in a conference at Stanford University held in October 1992, and while they do not represent a consensus of opinion or a uniformity of school or approach, they all share the recognition of the timeliness of such a reassessment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aLiterary Studies -- General Criticism and Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBrownlee, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCosta-Lima, Luiz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleischman, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGellrich, Jesse M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGumbrecht, Hans Ulrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHart, Thomas R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandauer, Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLerer, Seth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLerer, Seth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLindenberger, Herbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aN